{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.91,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89843"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1314"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4147"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department requesting a pregnancy test and contraception. She reports her last menstrual period was eight weeks ago. She discloses that she has been in a sexual relationship with her 25-year-old boyfriend for the past three months. She states that he is pressuring her to terminate the pregnancy if the test is positive. She desperately wants to ensure that she can\u0027t fall pregnant in future and is asking for contraception. She reveals that he has previously hit her and threatened her with violence. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is currently experiencing homelessness and not in contact with her family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. A urine pregnancy test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Schedule antenatal care appointment","Request dating ultrasound","Notify child protection services and social work","Prescribe oral contraception","Arrange termination of pregnancy referral"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several concerning features including a significant age difference between sexual partners, physical abuse, potential coercion, and statutory rape of a minor. The age difference makes this a clear case of child sexual abuse requiring mandatory reporting, while the disclosure of physical violence necessitates immediate social work involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENotify child protection services and social work\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as healthcare providers have a legal obligation to report suspected child sexual abuse. The significant age gap between the patient and her partner (14 vs 25 years) constitutes statutory rape, as persons under 16 years cannot legally consent to sexual activity with someone significantly older. The history of physical abuse makes this an urgent child protection matter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange termination of pregnancy referral\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature and potentially harmful without first addressing the safeguarding concerns and ensuring the patient is making an autonomous decision free from coercion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe oral contraception\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the immediate safeguarding concerns and could be seen as enabling ongoing abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest dating ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E, while eventually necessary if the pregnancy continues, does not address the immediate child protection concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchedule antenatal care appointment\u003C/strong\u003E would similarly fail to address the immediate safeguarding issues that require urgent attention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter making the mandatory report and involving social work, the clinician should provide supportive care, ensure the patient\u0027s immediate safety, and involve appropriate support services. Any decisions about the pregnancy should be made after ensuring the patient is safe and free from coercion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mandatory reporting is required when there is reasonable suspicion of child sexual abuse, including statutory rape.","Adolescents under 16 years cannot legally consent to sexual activity with someone significantly older.","Healthcare providers must balance confidentiality with child protection obligations.","Assessment of capacity for medical decision-making in adolescents requires evaluation of their understanding and voluntariness.","Social work involvement is essential in cases of suspected domestic violence and abuse."],"references":["Cundy TP. Sexual assault: A gynaecologist\u2019s perspective [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2012 [cited 2024 Nov 25];14(4). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/14/4-14/sexual-assault-gynaecologists-perspective/","Carter A, Hinchey J. Clinical management of patients presenting following sexual assault [Internet]. Aust J Gen Pract. 2020 Jul [cited 2024 Nov 25];49(7):423-8. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/july/clinical-management-of-patients-presenting-followi"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89843"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16402"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89843"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-28T16:42:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T10:26:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":n